  "text": "Previous studies of renal ischemia revealed that ischemic tissues and infiltrating inflammatory cells express iNOS and release reactive oxygen species and N-derived oxidants [CITATION_1] . As such, inhibition of iNOS attenuates ischemia reperfusion injury [CITATION_2] . In turn, oxidative stress is involved in the pathogenesis of ischemia-reperfusion injury by adding further insult to renal tissues and inducing the release of pro-inflammatory molecules, which recruit inflammatory cells into the interstitium [CITATION_3] . Consistent with these studies, we found significant increases in plasma and renal tissue levels of nitrite/nitrate with renal ischemia, which were attenuated by IP-treatment ( Figure 6A and 6B) . However, attenuation by IP was abolished in gene-targeted mice for the A2BAR (Figure 6A and 6B) . Similarly, iNOS activity was reduced in IP-treated renal tissues of A2BAR WT mice but not in A2BAR À/À mice ( Figure 6C ). Moreover, immunohistochemistry revealed a strong immune-reactivity for iNOS in macrophages following ischemia. Macrophage infiltration and iNOS expression was reduced following IP treatment of WT but not of A2BAR À/À mice ( Figure 6D-6I ). Taken together, these studies suggest that IP-associated attenuation of nitric oxide production involves signaling through the A2BAR.",
